Pour @cold salted water{300%ml} (double for 4p) into a #medium pot{} with a
tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover and cook for ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, remove the pot from the heat. Keep covered for another
~{12%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in
its own steam).

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @mushrooms{150%g}(roughly chopped).

Halve the @chilli{1}(halved and finely chopped) and discard the core and
seeds.

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces).

Stir the @coconut milk{1%pack} (or shake the packet) to dissolve any lumps.

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle}.

When the pan is hot, add the onion and mushrooms. Season with @salt{to taste}
and @pepper{to taste}.

Fry until browned, stirring occasionally, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the @garlic, ginger & lemongrass paste{1%sachet} and chilli (use less if you
don't like spice).

Fry until fragrant, another ~{30%seconds}.

Meanwhile, cut each @hake{250%g} fillet into four equal-sized pieces.

Add the fish, coconut milk and @water{25%ml} (double for 4p) to the pan.

Cover and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish. Fish is cooked
> when opaque in the middle.

Loosen the sauce with a splash of water if necessary. Season to taste with
salt and pepper.

While the fish cooks, trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}(thinly sliced).

Add the @honey{2%sachets} and @miso paste{1%sachet} to a #bowl{} and mix to
combine.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between bowls.

Top with the fragrant fish curry.

Drizzle the honey miso sauce over the hake.

Finish with a sprinkling of sliced scallion.